## Conflicts and Judgment Calls

- **Gemini=Accept vs. Opus=Major.** Opus's bar (mature external baseline, mmap measurement, real data) is real but disputable for a structures-and-algorithms TOMS paper. Tier 1 + items 10–13 together are the minimum that no reviewer can call insufficient. Item 14 is the cheapest concession to Opus M1; item 16 is the cheapest *refusal* of Opus M4 and should be defended explicitly in the response letter.
- **5D rhetoric (item 5) vs. 5D measurement (item 12).** Doing item 12 lets you keep the seismic motivation; skipping item 12 forces item 5. Pick one, not both.

## Suggested Sequencing

1. Tier 1 edits in one pass (no measurements needed). [DONE]
2. Items 10, 11, 12 in parallel — all reuse existing benchmark scaffolding. [12 DONE; 10, 11 pending]
3. Item 13 (flat-layout) once 10–12 are stable. [DONE 2026-04-30]
4. Item 14 only if 1–13 came in under budget. [DONE 2026-04-29]
5. Re-run `make benchmark` on every platform to populate the new `storage-*.txt` files (item 13 data); wire a new extractor `plot/storage-summary.cpp` and a corresponding subsection in the paper.
6. Draft the response letter mapping each reviewer comment to a section + commit hash, and explicitly justify the item 16 refusal.

